item.title: Venezuela's Maduro Takes Over Rival Political Parties
item.description: Nicolás Maduro’s regime stripped the license of one of the country’s largest parties and handed control to a pro-government ally, the latest in a string of measures to further weaken the opposition.

item.title: North Korea Blows Up Liaison Office With South
item.description: Ahead of the destruction of the jointly run facility, which closed earlier this year, Pyongyang had warned of military action in statements aimed at the South.

item.title: India-China Border Standoff Turns Violent, With 20 Indian Soldiers Dead
item.description: India said 20 of its soldiers died in a clash with Chinese troops along the two countries’ disputed border in the Himalayan Mountains, the worst military confrontation between the nuclear-armed neighbors in decades.

item.title: Coronavirus Contact-Tracing Apps Launch Across Europe
item.description: Germany became the largest Western country to launch a contact-tracing smartphone app to help curb the spread of the coronavirus, but the app’s effectiveness will depend on how many people use it.

item.title: Hungarian Parliament Ends Controversial State of Emergency
item.description: Hungary’s Parliament voted to end a state of emergency that gave Prime Minister Viktor Orban the right to rule by decree.

item.title: U.S. Work With WHO Continues, Weeks After Trump's Vow to Quit
item.description: The U.S. has taken no formal step to leave the agency and WHO staff continue to work at U.S. government agencies.
